Those three methods (`OnStart`, `OnSleep`, `OnResume`) **still exist** on `Application` in .NET MAUI, so your overrides will compile. However, MAUI also introduces a more granular model via the `Window` class:

| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window equivalent |
|---|---|
| `OnStart` | `OnCreated` / `OnActivated` |
| `OnSleep` | `OnDeactivated` / `OnStopped` |
| `OnResume` | `OnResumed` / `OnActivated` |

**Recommended approach** — override `CreateWindow` and use a custom `Window`:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = new Window(new MainPage());

        window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };
        window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };
        window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };
        window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* cleanup */ };

        return window;
    }
}
```

For **platform-specific** hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnStop(activity => { /* ... */ }));
#elif IOS
    events.AddiOS(ios => ios.WillTerminate(app => { /* ... */ }));
#endif
});
```

**TL;DR:** Your existing overrides still work, but the `Window` events give you finer control and better multi-window support.
